default2.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultHow DFID cdefaultould changedefault.  
defaultReturn
defaulting to the “twin track” approach
default, it is well known that this comprises targeted work to meet the particular needs of disabled people, for example rehab
defaultilitation or social assistance, together with barrier removal to ensure that disability is mainstreamed across all development activities.  I think the work I did with WHO to mainstream disability show
defaultcase
defaults some of the necessary elements of a successful st
defaultrategy:
default2.1.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultLeadership from the topdefault: the Director General initiated the Task Force on Disability, and it was chaired by a WHO Assistant Director General, Dr Ala Alwan.   A Director, Dr Etienne Krug, provided operational leadership.   I was able to point to the
defaultse champions to open doors and ensure that people realised that disability was an organizational priority.  Dr Chan mentioned disability inclusion in several key speeches during the WHO reform period and spoke at the launch of the World report on disabilit
defaulty.  She also supported a World Health Assembly resolution in 2013.
default2.1.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultA staff member with disability driving changedefault: I was a visible and confident advocate of disability inclusion.  I had face to face meetings with more than 50 directors where we discussed th
defaulte priorities and opportunities for disability mainstreaming. I visited the regional offices in Europe, Americas, Western Pacific and Eastern Mediterranean region and gave presentations. 
default2.1.3
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultMainstreamingdefault comprised work with technical departments such as Repro
defaultductive Health Research or Health Action in Crises.  This led to disability-inclusive initiatives, such as a guidance note on sexual and reproductive health for persons with disabilities, and a policy brief on HIV and disability, and resources on disabilit
defaulty in disasters.
default2.1.4
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultBarrier removaldefault comprised work with key WHO service departments.  For example, I worked with the Human Resources team to train members of selection panels on disability equality.  We achieved a “welcome st
defaultatement” on advertisements that
default stressed diversity in general, rather than being limited to women and under-represented nationalities.  We promoted the concept of reasonable accommodation and explored how this could be delivered for staff and interns with disabilities.  I also worked wi
defaultth WHO Press and the Communications teams to explore making information resources more accessible.  For example, this included making WHO reports available for people with visual impairment and Easy Read versions for people with intellectual disabilities. 
default  WHO videos were subtitled for the first time.  We also audited HQ and regional offices for disabled access, and invested in barrier removal around buildings.
default2.1.5
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultRegular face-to-face meetingsdefault were necessary to ensure that agreements were followed up and impl
defaultemented.  There were also quarterly meetings of the Task Force itself, which included a representative from all the key service sections, all the headquarters clusters, and the regional offices.  This meant that disability became an issue for the whole org
defaultanisation, not just for the rather small Disability and Rehabilitation team. 
default2.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultI note that AusAid conducted a similar process with their Disability Inclusive Development strategy, but that they were able to be more systematic, for example 
defaultin ensuring that all staff members had training in disability equality, and that there was a detailed change process to ensure that everyone understood and promoted the strategy.
default   In retrospect, I think this more structural approach to implementing disabi
defaultlity inclusion would have been advisable for WHO, and would be preferable for DFID.
default&#xa0;
default3
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWhile disability is not simply a health issue, hdefaultealthdefault is a vital issue for many disabled peopledefault.  The strong emphasis that many British and developing world activists place on the social model of disability should not obscure the fact that for many of the world’s billion disabled people, access to health is a pressing concern.  For example, 
defaultInternat
defaultional Perspectives on Spinal Cord Injury
default (WHO 2013) highlights how many people who develop SCI die within a year or two of injury – as was the case in the UK, prior to the pioneering work of Ludwig Guttman after World War 2.   What is lacking is not high t
defaultech medicine, but nursing and health information and assistive technologies (wheelchairs, cushions, catheters) to  prevent avoidable health problems such as urinary tract infections and pressure sores.
default3.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default Similarly, mortality is disproportionately high for b
defaultabies and children with disabilities, often because of neglect, in some cases verging on manslaughter.  Infants may not get adequate nutrition, may not be immunised, or may not be considered valuable enough to merit health and education.  Evidence from res
defaultearch with infants with spina bifida in Uganda published by Warf et al (2011) highlights how comparatively simple interventions – in this case a Community Based Rehabilitation programme ensuring that families were visited every couple of weeks – could make
default the difference between life and death: for infants in the CBR programme, five year 
defaultmortality was equivalent to non-disabled peers.  For infants outside the programme, it was three times higher.
default3.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultDespite the salience of health, evidence from the World repor
defaultt on disability (WHO 2011) shows how disabled people were twice as likely to find healthcare provider skills and equipment inadequate to meet their needs, three times as likely to be denied care, and four times as likely to be treated badly.  We know from 
defaultUK experiences that people with intellectual disabilities and mental health conditions are particularly likely to receive worse care, and consequently to have higher mortality.
default3.3
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultTherefore I would advocate for DFID work on health to include
default disability, not simply as an issue of prevention – although prevention of avoidable impairment must remain a priority – but also as an issue of access and equity.  In particular, training of health professionals to understand the health and human rights o
defaultf disabled people should contribute to more appropriate, accessible and inclusive services.  I will never forget the testimony of one disabled woman in West Africa, who reported that, when she presented at a hospital in the early stages of labour, health w
defaultorkers laughed at her and asked how on earth she could have managed to get pregnant.
default  Another aspect of health systems which needs to be prioritised is supply of rehabilitation personnel – mid-level rehabilitation therapists in particular – which is almost
default always inadequate   in low income countries, even though rehabilitation interventions can ensure a person returns to education and employment after having an impairment such as SCI or brain injury or being born with cerebral palsy.
default&#xa0;
default4
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultFinally, to say a few 
defaultwords about 
defaultdisability datadefault.  WHO will doubtless make their own submission on this topic.  My own opinion is that there are two different needs.  Given that data is lacking, there is an urgent need to understand the prevalence of disability and the experie
defaultnce of disabled people, particularly the role of disabled barriers.  This requires effective survey approaches based on the ICF, such as the WHO Model Disability Survey which is currently in cognitive and field testing.  
default4.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultHowever, there is another need whi
defaultch is simpler, and for which the Washington Group’s Six Questions have always seemed to me to be a practical solution.  This is the disaggregation of disability data, to enable monitoring of service use and outcomes for disabled people.  Unless it can be s
defaulthown how disabled people are experiencing particular needs, or how those needs are being met, then it will be much harder to develop strategies for disability inclusion.  
default4.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultConceptually, my understanding of disability is somewhat different from either the “
defaultmedical model” or the “social model”.  In line with the ICF, I see disability as a multi-factorial phenomenon
default (Shakespeare 2006)
default.  Taking a critical realist perspective, I understand disability as impacting at different levels – medical, psychological, phy
defaultsical environment, social, educational, employment, law, politics, culture etc.  We can intervene at one or more of these different levels – for example, by providing medical interventions or by removing barriers, or by passing anti-discrimination laws, or
default promoting awareness campaigns.  All these different responses are useful, in principle.  For certain groups or in certain contexts, one type of intervention may be a higher priority than another.
default4.3
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWhen I worked with the Task Force on Disability, Directors 
defaultof WHO technical departments would always first ask me about the data on disabled people in their area of concern.  If I could not point to public health evidence that disabled people were disproportionately at risk, they would 
defaultnot take my human rights arg
defaultuments so seriously.  A combination of disaggregated data, “quick and dirty” if need be, together with other human rights and economics arguments is the only way to persuade colleagues and also governments in low income countries that investment in improvi
defaultng the lives of disabled people is a good buy and will produce significant outcomes at a population level.
default4.4
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultTherefore I hope that DFID will invest in monitoring and evaluation, support governments in LMIC to invest in disaggregated data and disability surve
defaultys, so that we can know better what the problems are, and how they can be remedied.  It was very striking, as we prepared the World report on disability, that we could not make firm evidence-based recommendations in many areas, because the data was lacking
default.
